  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>THE DARKNESS AND THE BALANCE II--A SMALL UPRISING</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p><b>Chapter 2- A Small Uprising</b></p>

<p>Garlin spoke first when they entered the village.</p>

<p> “Fear not my friends, these elves have come for our protection.  They also need our help.” </p>

<p>At Garlin’s words, the Halflings relaxed.  Some of them started hustling about and speaking amongst themselves.  One of them approached Garlin. </p>  

<p> “Sir, the barbarian from the north has arrived.  He is waiting in your hut.” </p>

<p> “Thank you.  I must leave you Zarx.  The healers hut is over there you will be treated as a member of the village.  Go now, he needs his rest and quickly.” </p>

<p>Zarx took off to the hut followed by Ndarye and Gaan, who was still suspicious and was not going to let those dark elves out of his sight.  They stepped into the hut and the two Halflings that were there smiled at them and lead them to a bed.  Zarx laid Zeryl down and stepped away and allowed Ndarye to work. </p>

<p> “I am going to go see Garlin while you work Ndarye.” </p>

<p>Ndarye nodded and shut her eyes.  Gaan was now torn.  Ndarye looked innocent enough so he decided to follow Zarx.  When they got to Garlin’s hut, Zarx started to walk in. </p>

<p> “Excuse me Zarx, but shouldn’t you knock?” </p>

<p>Zarx stopped and turned to Gaan.  His tone was harsh but soft. </p>

<p> “Listen to me little one.  I knock for no one.  I go where I please, and I do not listen to worthless little Halflings like yourself so shut your mouth and do not bother me with your idle drivel.” </p>

<p>In the room, Garlin was talking to a huge male barbarian, who was hunched over almost doubled.  </p>

<p> “Ahhh Zarx.  This is Helfgar.  He has come to take on the same quest you seek my friend.  He says his gods have spoken and shown his people the prophecy.” </p>

<p>Zarx eyed Helfgar suspiciously. </p>

<p> “The “gods” he speaks of know nothing of the prophecy or its implication in Norrath, but it does affect all races, so he is welcome.” </p>

<p>Helfgar spoke in a deep voice that shook the hut. </p> 

<p> “Ahh I see another elf that stereotypes beyond what he knows is good for him.  I appreciate the welcome though.  Garlin speaks very well of you and so your small oversight is forgiven.” </p>

<p> “Bah, I seek no forgiveness from you.  But again I welcome any help on the quest we must undertake.” </p>

<p>Helfgar ducked through the door and walked back out into the forest. </p> 

<p> “Dark place you elves have here.” </p>

<p> “Yes, but it suits us.” </p>

<p> “So Garlin says you think you have found him.” </p>

<p> “I know I have, he is in the healers hut.  We must set out for High Keep to see Tarn Vislin.  He is the first of the masters to see before we reach our final destination.” </p>

<p> “Yes I know.” </p>

<p>Zarx stared at the barbarian for a moment surprised at his union with the essence of the environment.  Maybe the teachings of his race were wrong about the race that others deem inferior.  He watched Helfgar approach the healing hut when he stopped.  His eyes got wide and he knelt on the ground.  He mumbled what seemed to be a prayer in some archaic language. As he finished, Zeryl came out of the hut.  He was wearing a blue robe with the markings of the sun on the shoulders.  The light, or what there was of it, seemed to burn his eyes as he exited the hut and he took in his surroundings.  Ndarye followed behind him.  Helfgar stood up and greeted Zeryl. </p>

<p> “Good day to you oh noble one.” </p>

<p>Zeryl looked at him in shock. </p>

<p> “Noble?  I assure you sir I take no part in Dark elf nobility or any other nobility for that matter.  I have been banished for my actions and have nothing, not even family.” </p>

<p>Helfgar looked back to Zarx with confusion but said nothing further. </p>  

<p>Zarx was still surprised at the knowledge Helfgar seemed to have.  His gods were supposed to be archaic and dead to Norrath but he received knowledge of the prophecy and the revelation of the one as soon as Zeryl exited the hut but his suspicions would have to wait.  He stepped forward to greet Zeryl and introduce himself. </p>

<p> “I am Zarx.  The elf who healed you is named Ndarye.  This is Helfgar and he will aide us on our quest as well.” </p>

<p> “Quest?  I am on no quest my brother.  But I do see that you carry the mark as I do.  Why so?” </p>

<p> “For many of the same reasons you do, though I by no means defied the Counsel or its god as you did.  I simply put the prophecy before them, and they would have no part of it.” </p>

<p> “You mean the prophecy of Nidus?” </p>

<p> “That is exactly what I mean.  We believe that you will bring balance again to this world.” </p>

<p>Zeryl begin to smile and then he laughed.  Zarx and Helfgar looked at each other surprised at his reaction.  </p>

<p> “No, no I could not be the one spoken of.  My parents share the same race they are both dark elves and have abandoned me for their names sake.  The chosen one is said to be born out of conflict and will bring conflict to his people.” </p>

<p> “I speak for Halas. And Sir Zeryl you have all the makings of the noble ones according to our ancient scrolls.  Conflict to your people I believe you have brought, as for the conflict of birth, I do not know your past but am still lead to believe you are who this noble elf has stated.” </p>

<p> “Personally sir, I believe that all you elves are nuts and would just like a chance to go out and fight like Zarx has said.” </p>

<p>All were surprised by Gaan’s intervention in their conversation.  Zarx looked at him. </p>

<p> “You think you are going with us?” </p>

<p> “I would be honored to work by your side and am pretty good with a weapon.” </p>

<p> “Zarx let the lad along.  Surely he could be no worse to us than nothing.” </p>

<p> “Yes, at least he’ll make somewhat of a meatsheild.” </p>

<p> “Wait.  I still stand confused.  I do not believe that I hold the power of the prophecy within in me, nonetheless, I will accompany you on whatever journey you seek in order to prove the point.” </p>

<p>Zarx conceded.  He knew once they could speak with Tarn Vislin, that this matter would be cleared up and he would be correct as usual. </p>

<p> “Very well.  We have much to do to prepare.  And our journey lies through the enchanted forest Kithicor. </p> 

************************************************************************
<p>Somewhere beyond the realm of the mortal plane, a large dark figure sat and brooded on his next move.  He thought of the many things that he must do in the next little while and he also pondered the words of Nidus.  He paid them little regard but nonetheless action must begin for his God was waiting to come into the world.  He stood up and began his orders to his disciples. </p>

<p> “The Darkness is near.  Our time is at hand.  The mortals will resist but fear not.  Darkness shall conquer in the end.  Now go minions and reek havoc upon the mortal plane.” </p>

<p>Creatures of all sorts stood up and left their spot in the plane of Hate for their god had spoken and they knew no better than to follow his command.  They flew to all parts of Norrath for though their god was powerful, the power that waited to enter this plane was far beyond anything they could imagine. </p>

************************************************************************
<p>Kozo sat in the cave reading over some of his ancient scrolls.  He couldn’t logically figure how or where this so called “one” would show up or if he even would exist.  Afterall he was reading about him or her from a scroll written well over a millinia ago.  Whether or not it was true remained to be seen, but the foreboding outcome was not a pretty sight and he was determined to set out to keep it from happening.  As gnomes always thought, … better safe than sorry. </p>

<p>He continued to search for answers as his raven familiar fly in from a window.  He perched on Kozo’s shoulder and pecked at his glasses. </p> 

<p> “Stop that Nidus.” </p>

<p>Nidus.  He thought about the name.  He ran across it in some of the scrolls and it grew on him so he called his bird Nidus.  Just then Nidus pecked so hard his glasses fell off and dropped onto the scroll. </p> 

<p> “You foolish old thing!!” </p>

<p>He brushed the bird away and went to retrieve his glasses.  He paused over the place which they magnified and noticed a mark that he hadn’t seen before. </p>

<p> “By Golly Hoop!!  You found it Nidus.  This script was reading “the forest of <i>daylight</i>” but this mark makes the word “<i>darkness</i>”.  It could only be Kithikor!!  And the date is so soon I must go…I must prepare!  Oh so much to do so much to do.  Nidus help!” </p>

<p>Kozo scrambled around with excitement for a bit more and gathered his things; then set off for the forest of Darkness. </p>
 </font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><small>By <b>Xzenus</b> Submited on 11/16/2001</small></td>
